post_text: This week’s episode of the 9th Grade Experience features EHS School Nurse, Beth Ann Hendershot; 11th Grade Assistant Principal, Greg Annoni; along with students Joshua Jones and David Svoboda talking about a variety of wellness issues. Some of the topics include the importance of establishing healthy routines, taking brain breaks and getting physical activity during your day, avoiding social isolation as much as possible, and reconnection with family and past hobbies that may have been forgotten. Also, we hear from Mr. Annoni about some of the behind-the-scenes things that have allowed the first weeks of this new eLearning to function smoothly.

text:
This week’s episode of the 9th Grade Experience features EHS School Nurse, Beth Ann Hendershot; 11th Grade Assistant Principal, Greg Annoni; along with students Joshua Jones and David Svoboda talking about a variety of wellness issues. Some of the topics include the importance of establishing healthy routines, taking brain breaks and getting physical activity during your day, avoiding social isolation as much as possible, and reconnection with family and past hobbies that may have been forgotten. Also, we hear from Mr. Annoni about some of the behind-the-scenes things that have allowed the first weeks of this new eLearning to function smoothly.

ANCHOR.FM
Season 2, Episode 24: Coronavirus Update Week 5 by The 9th Grade Experience • A podcast on Anchor

COVID-19 Update-East Penn School District Closure Extended

As announced today by Governor Tom Wolf, the East Penn School District will be extending its closure through April 8, 2020. We ask that you continue to follow the guidance of health officials that includes social distancing and do what is asked to prevent the community spread of COVID-19.

We will update you in a district communication tomorrow regarding our continued learning plan that the Office of Teaching and Learning has developed for our students. Thank you for your continued support and understanding as we work to make decisions in the best interests of our entire school community.

post_text: As we approach the end of our first week of our Coronavirus shutdown in the East Penn School District, the 9th Grade Experience checks in with 9th graders to see how they are adjusting the new reality we are all living in. Via Instagram and Google Classroom, they asked students to tell us about what they have been up to, the establishment of new routines, and how they are feeling about the whole situation. While some answers were not shocking (sleeping, eating, and playing video games), a few were unexpected, as they wrote about how much they missed the routine of school and their friends.

As we approach the end of our first week of our Coronavirus shutdown in the East Penn School District, the 9th Grade Experience checks in with 9th graders to see how they are adjusting the new reality we are all living in. Via Instagram and Google Classroom, they asked students to tell us about what they have been up to, the establishment of new routines, and how they are feeling about the whole situation. While some answers were not shocking (sleeping, eating, and playing video games), a few were unexpected, as they wrote about how much they missed the routine of school and their friends.

post_text:
In an effort to allow our students to remain cognitively engaged while away from school, our grade level teams and departments developed menus of independent learning options to share with students and families. These activities are optional for students, will not be graded, and will not introduce any new learning. Recognizing that not all students have access to technology, we intentionally created a balance of both online and offline activities. In addition, if a student has access to Google Classroom or Schoology, their teacher may post additional information. This work will also remain optional and ungraded.

https://docs.google.com/document/d/1zlYJWdScGT5PB3is66kxBonOH1zHD1ZLR7ucvLhdQVk/view

post_text:
Seven Emmaus High School students have been chosen to sing at the Pennsylvania Music Educators Association All-State Chorus Festival on April 22-25 at Kalahari Resorts & Convention Center in Pocono Manor. The festival will feature more than 200 of the best high school choral singers from across the state. Students were selected for All-State Chorus through auditions at Region Chorus Festivals. There are six regions in Pennsylvania and Emmaus students auditioned at PMEA Region 5 Chorus Festival at Eastern York High School in February.

Named to All-State Chorus are Rachel Knappenberger, Soprano I; Maya Schlesinger, Soprano II; Alena Slak, Alto I; Danielle Potts, Alto II; Rhys Williams, Tenor I; Lorenzo Antigua, Tenor II and Trevor Warren, Bass II.

The School Counselors of EHS will be available for a lunch hour conversation with parents/guardians of 9th, 10th, and 11th grade students for a course selection/scheduling workshop. post_text: On February 20th, students from the American Computer Science League (ACSL) club hosted the 5th annual programming competition, EHS Code Buzz 2020. Eighteen teams from ten different schools had three hours to complete ten programming problems that were designed by the following club members: Arti Schmidt, Cameron Fanning, Geoffrey Kleinberg, Ishaan Lal, and Jamie Kahle. Students in computer science classes stayed after school on an Act 80 day to beta test the programs. They then served as judges during the competition. Great job, ACSL!

post_text: Wescosville Elementary School participated in the "Souper Bowl of Caring.” WES students brought in canned goods and non-perishable food items to donate. Each item was counted and boxed by the members of the Wescosville Community Service Club. Each food item earned the homeroom a yard on the giant football field. The classes enjoyed seeing their class helmet move down the field each day toward a touchdown. The school collected 2107 food items donated to Groceries Plus Emmaus Food Bank. Mrs. Eisenhard's second grade class was the winning class collecting 380 cans! They won a trophy and an extra gym class. Congratulations, everyone!

post_text:
Today, all EHS students will receive a wristband that states, 'You are Special, You are Loved, and Your Life Matters.' These wristbands have been provided to promote suicide prevention awareness within our school community. We want our students to know that the faculty and staff at Emmaus High School values them as individuals and cares deeply about their well-being. Our hope is that members of our school community will wear this wristband to show their support for this very important cause.

Always remember, you never know who is going through a difficult time. By wearing this wristband and reading those few simple, yet powerful words, you are reminding someone they are not alone.

post_text: Are you interested in visiting the Charles Darwin Research Station? Visiting a giant tortoise breeding center and pink flamingo habitat? Visiting a cloud forest and lava tunnels? Snorkeling with sea lions and exotic fish? If so, this amazing biology-related trip to the Galápagos Islands in the Summer of 2022 is for you!! Current 8th, 9th and 10th graders who are interested can come to an informational parent/student meeting on Thursday, December 12, 6:30 PM in Room 420 of Emmaus HS. If you’re interested in more information, please contact Mr. Bisignani, Mrs. Hess, Mrs. Kramer or Mr. Landrum. Visit the tour link to check it out!!

post_text: Mrs. Shingler's 8th grade, Zone Team, ELA classes participated in a writing contest sponsored by Young Writers USA called Mission Contamination. They wrote 100-word mini-sagas about something that contaminated the world and is threatening humanity. Sixty six students' sagas were chosen out of the 120+ entered. They received certificates and will be published in a book by Young Writers USA. A copy of the book will be given to the LMMS library, so their writing will live on forever at LMMS! They will also be treated to a Zone Team pizza party! Congratulations to these fine young writers!

post_text:
East Penn School District and STA are joining forces this holiday season!!

STA will be holding a “Stuff the Bus” event this December. An East Penn bus will be parked outside each school for 2 days just waiting to be stuffed! Below is a list of new items that your students can bring in to help make someone else’s holiday bright:

-Hats
-Scarves
-Gloves/Mittens
-Coats
-Snowsuits
-Snow Boots/Rain Boots
-Raincoats
-Ear muffs

To the school that collects the most items, STA will donate $250.00 to the schools PTO.

Dates the bus will be at the schools is as follows:

Macungie and Shoemaker: December 5th and 6th
Eyer and LMMS: December 9th and 10th
Wescosville and Alburtis: December 11th and 12th
Lincoln and Jefferson: December 16th and 17th
Emmaus High School and Willow: December 18th and 19th

post_text: On Tuesday, October 22nd, five Emmaus High School students competed at Dickinson College in the Capital Area Math Competition. The team of Ishaan Lal, Caitlin O'Brien, Geoffrey Kleinberg, and Arti Schmidt brought home 1st place in the team competition by answering 25 of 35 questions in the Quiz Bowl correct. Ishaan placed 1st, Geoffrey placed 3rd, and Carter Lowell placed 9th in the individual tests. Ishaan scored an amazing 20/20 on the free response section of the individual contest. Congrats to them all!

post_text: The Emmaus Police Department will be at EHS on Tuesday, October 15th thru Friday, October 18th making sure you are wearing your seat belt. Driving comes with great responsibility. You are not only responsible for yourself but also for making sure passengers in your vehicle are buckled up too! Our state allows anyone under 18 to be pulled over and ticketed for not wearing a seat belt. So, buckle up, law enforcement will be writing tickets to save lives!
